    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-21T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-21T03:00:00-05:00" n="61"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d61">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/6879: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Legation in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-21T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 21, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 21—11:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>37. My 28, February 11, 11 a.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>I respectfully invite the Department’s attention to published accounts of
                        address delivered by the Chinese Minister for Foreign Affairs to the Central
                        Political Council on December [<hi rend="italic">February</hi>] 20 described
                        by him as an explanation of China’s policy toward Japan. The address
                        advanced various reasons for special friendship between the two countries
                        including sentiments uttered by Sun Yat-sen in a speech delivered at Kobe,
                        1924.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Press reports here are to the effect that Wang Chung-hui<note n="54"
                            xml:id="d61fn54">Judge, Permanent Court of International Justice at The
                            Hague.</note> called on the Japanese Premier and Minister of War on
                        February 20th.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Report not yet confirmed has been received that the Japanese Government
                        has extended an invitation to the Chinese Government to send an economic
                        mission to Japan and that the Chinese Government will find it impossible to
                        refuse.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
